{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491051"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:30:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:30:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"815"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/815"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.02,0.85,0.04,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"815"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"29849"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/815"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"815"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15839"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"665"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6558"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7449"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7798"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42156"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44570"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44894"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"29849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/29849"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a three hour history of sudden onset and sharp chest pain. He feels sweaty and has difficulty breathing. His medical history includes hypertension for which he is currently taking perindopril and atorvastatin.  On examination he looks unwell, with a blood pressure of 100/75 mmHg, pulse 105/min, temperature 36.5\u2103, respiration rate 20/min, body and SaO2 of 99% on room air. He has a soft diastolic murmur and the rest of his chest examination is unremarkable. An ECG shows sinus tachycardia. A chest X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pulmonary embolus","Acute myocardial infarction","Aortic dissection","Tension pneumothorax","Pericarditis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis X-ray demonstrates a widened mediastinum, and in combination with the chest pain indicates a likely diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Eaortic dissection\u003C/strong\u003E. Risk factors for aortic dissection include inherited disease (such as Marfan\u0027s syndrome, Ehler-Danlos type IV), hypertension, previous surgery, infection and increasing age. The pain is described as sudden, severe and tearing, and may radiate to the back or abdomen. It can also mimic the pain of an acute myocardial infarction. The diastolic murmur present is indicative of aortic regurgitation which can occur with aortic dissection. Based on the Stanford classification, Type A involves the ascending aorta, and Type B involves the aorta beyond the left subclavian artery only.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute myocardial infarction\u003C/strong\u003E is a possible differential, and important to consider, although this is more likely to show ECG changes and does not explain the chest X-ray findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary embolus\u003C/strong\u003E would be associated with sinus tachycardia, however chest X-rays are not specific for pulmonary emboli. \u003Cstrong\u003EPericarditis\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with pleuritic pain, and an ECG would show widespread ST-elevation. A chest X-ray may demonstrate pericardial effusion. A\u003Cstrong\u003E tension pneumothorax\u003C/strong\u003E is a collapsed lung, associated with pleuritic chest pain and shortness of breath. On chest X-ray, there will be decreased lung marking due to lack of air in the pleural cavity and depending on the severity, may also demonstrate mediastinal shift.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Aortic dissection is an emergency with high mortality and morbidity rate.","Management priorities in aortic dissection is to control blood pressure, bleeding, fluid resuscitation and consider surgery.","Surgery is often indicated in Type A, while Type B can often be medically managed with blood pressure control."],"references":["Nickson, C. Acute Aortic Dissection. Life in the Fast Lane [Internet]. 2020 Nov. Available from: https://litfl.com/acute-aortic-dissection/","Hacking, C., Bell, D. Mediastinal widening (differential). Reference article, Radiopaedia.org. https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-49876","Levy D, Goyal A, Grigorova Y, et al. Aortic Dissection. [Updated 2022 May 2]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441963/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15839"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"815"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18143"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18143"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8482ef94-4b72-4117-8102-88074dc96ddf.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici